'''Coign and livery''' or '''coyne and livery''' ({{lang-ga|coinmheadh is buannacht<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focal.ie/Search.aspx?term=coign+and+livery&lang=3116649|title=coign and livery|work=[[Focal (lexicographical website)|Focal]]|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>}}) in [[Gaelic Ireland]] was the free entertainment which a chief exacted from his subjects for his servants and followers. Originally in [[Brehon law]] it took the form of a [[banquet|feast]] held when the chief passed through a subject's lands. By the late medieval period it was often an oppressive charge to [[billet]] and supply the chief's professional soldiers ([[Kern (soldier)|kern]] and [[gallowglass]]es), enforced by those same soldiers. It was the most important of the exactions which lesser chiefs resented of their superiors.<ref name="bbc20110211">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/tudors/elizabeth_ireland_01.shtml|title=History - Turning Ireland English|last=Ellis|first=Steven|date=11 February 2011|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The [[surrender and regrant]] and [[Composition of Connacht|composition]] imposed by the English during the [[Tudor conquest of Ireland]] sought to abolish Gaelic customs of chiefship and replace all exactions with a single rent charged on land holdings.<ref name="bbc20110211"/> This was accordingly supported by the lesser chiefs, but opposed by the over chiefs such as [[Gerald FitzGerald, 11th Earl of Kildare]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carey|first=Vincent P.|date=Summer 1994|title=Collaborator and Survivor? Gerald the eleventh Earl of Kildare and Tudor Rule in Ireland|journal=History Ireland|volume=2|issue=2|url=http://www.historyireland.com/early-modern-history-1500-1700/collaborator-and-survivor-gerald-the-eleventh-earl-of-kildare-and-tudor-rule-in-ireland/}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Purveyance]], English equivalent * [[Quartering Acts]], requiring American colonies to billet British soldiers; one of the grievances that led to the American Revolution
